<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="13">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="13">
<taxonomicName authorityName="R. B. Zhang, D. Tan &amp; C. B. Ma" authorityYear="2020" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Lamiaceae" genus="Paraphlomis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Paraphlomis kuankuoshuiensis" order="Lamiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="kuankuoshuiensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">Paraphlomis kuankuoshuiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from the morphologically similar species 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. patentisetulosa" pageId="0" pageNumber="13" rank="species" species="patentisetulosa">P. patentisetulosa</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. hispida" pageId="0" pageNumber="13" rank="species" species="hispida">P. hispida</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
, and 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. hirsutissima" pageId="0" pageNumber="13" rank="species" species="hirsutissima">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">P. hirsutissima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its very short stem (&lt;7 cm) with one or two short internodes (giving the impression of having a tuft of basal leaves). The three closely related species have stems longer than 15 cm and more internodes. The new species has sparsely setose hairs on the outer surface of the calyces (vs. finely or densely) and short fruiting calyces (5-6 cm vs. 7 cm, 8-9 cm, and to 11 cm). There are some other diagnostic characters between the new species and its three closely related species (Table 
<tableCitation captionStart="Table 1" captionStartId="T1" captionText="Table 1. Comparing the diagnostics of Paraphlomis kuankuoshuiensis sp. nov., P. patentisetulosa, P. hispida, and P. hirsutissima." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/1A79708838AD57E26C780916CDD0544D" pageId="0" pageNumber="13" tableUuid="1A79708838AD57E26C780916CDD0544D">1</tableCitation>
). The flowering from July to August and fruiting from August to September are quite different from the three species (vs. fruiting from November to January). It grows on bare steep rocks, which is a distinctive habitat. The new species distributes in Guizhou Province and is far away from the other three species (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. The geographical distribution of Paraphlomis kuankuoshuiensis sp. nov. and its three closely related species." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.139.47055.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/371993" pageId="0" pageNumber="13">3</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
